1
00:00:01,415 --> 00:00:18,629
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:18,862 --> 00:00:33,040
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sammasambuddhasam Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:33,642 --> 00:00:47,418
So this evening I just want to revise a lot of what we've said about the skills, these skills of meditation, and see if any questions arise from it.

4
00:00:52,225 --> 00:00:59,037
I think one thing, well the first important thing is to recognize what these techniques are.

5
00:01:01,884 --> 00:01:09,457
Often we think it's, we might make the mistake of thinking that it's the technique which is

6
00:01:10,281 --> 00:01:35,326
creating the insight you might say if you get the technique perfectly perfectly right insight is bound to arise but if you look at other areas such as you know sports tennis things like that or instrument playing you know these musicians and sports people they spend hours practicing

7
00:01:36,370 --> 00:02:04,959
the backhand over and over again or going up and down the scales but then when it comes to actually playing the game playing the instrument it's a different situation isn't it because if they are thinking about their skills then it's going to sound pretty turgid they're definitely going to miss being in the moment when the shot comes over they're more worried about what their backhand is like I had a friend you know in

8
00:02:05,192 --> 00:02:28,467
Bangkok who was the Chinese and he was Australian champion for table tennis and he said he before he got this and he actually on one game beat the world champion which was very good he thought for himself but to do this he'd gone to Japan and he said the Japanese know how to train you

9
00:02:29,593 --> 00:02:56,377
and he's Chinese and he said they have a really rigorous training program which really lifts your game but the Japanese don't win and he said the reason for this is that they can't stop practicing they can't actually just play the game let the practice go and just play the game they're still too bothered about getting the shot right or something like that so

10
00:02:56,560 --> 00:03:25,774
these techniques are the same all they're doing is laying the ground preparing a basis for insight to arise but the insight itself arises because of the power of your attentiveness so all these exercises all these techniques are doing are just helping you to attain the right sort of attentiveness the right sort of focus

11
00:03:25,753 --> 00:03:27,997
and pointing you in the right direction.

12
00:03:29,919 --> 00:03:42,293
And, of course, this intuition that we talk about, this satipaññā, this intuitive awareness, is beyond the control of me, see?

13
00:03:43,133 --> 00:03:48,340
I can't sit here and say, well, I'm going to meditate now for an hour and I'm going to have an insight into Nibbāna.

14
00:03:50,663 --> 00:03:53,466
Of course, it doesn't work like that, it's very frustrating.

15
00:03:54,745 --> 00:04:04,236
Again, I'm reminded of somebody I met who, this is going way back when Vipassana was just coming in, you know, as a practice in the 70s or something.

16
00:04:04,257 --> 00:04:08,943
And he said he'd heard about this course, meditation, Nibbana, you see.

17
00:04:09,364 --> 00:04:13,288
So he joined a week's course and it's like anything else.

18
00:04:13,329 --> 00:04:20,077
If you do a course, you know, in cookery or something or whatever, they tell you what you'll achieve by the end of the course and you get a certificate.

19
00:04:21,425 --> 00:04:26,572
So he'd presume that, you know, one week he'd get Nibbana and get his certificate.

20
00:04:28,634 --> 00:04:34,223
It gave him a huge disappointment when he realized it wasn't quite like that.

21
00:04:34,242 --> 00:04:47,161
So these techniques are to be seen for what they are, just simple techniques preparing the ground for the real, an actual moment-to-moment mindfulness that the Buddha talks about.

22
00:04:51,800 --> 00:05:02,312
And you can see when you're getting caught up in that, when you're getting too worried about whether you're doing the technique right, whether you've got it perfect.

23
00:05:02,973 --> 00:05:10,463
It's like there's something wrong there if somebody is really getting anxious about, am I doing it right?

24
00:05:10,723 --> 00:05:13,766
Have I got it perfect?

25
00:05:15,449 --> 00:05:21,216
So be careful of that idea of perfection as such.

26
00:05:24,502 --> 00:05:40,891
The other thing to say about techniques is that it's not so good to mix them, because these various vipassana techniques do have their own pros and cons, they've got their own drawbacks and their own advantages.

27
00:05:40,872 --> 00:05:49,942
And if you mix it, it's sometimes confusing for the teacher, especially if you don't tell them what you're doing.

28
00:05:49,961 --> 00:06:04,617
So it's good to keep on one line because the teacher generally can spot or can see when something goes wrong from the report that the meditator gives, you see.

29
00:06:06,050 --> 00:06:07,874
But if they're mixing stuff, it doesn't work.

30
00:06:07,894 --> 00:06:09,980
It's like these alternative medicines, isn't it?

31
00:06:10,060 --> 00:06:13,166
You're not supposed to do acupuncture and homeopathy.

32
00:06:13,528 --> 00:06:20,225
It confuses both the acupuncturists and the homeopaths because you're getting the effects in both.

33
00:06:20,786 --> 00:06:23,653
So this is much the same.

34
00:06:29,302 --> 00:06:54,584
all these techniques have arisen out of some teacher so this is the Mahāzī and these techniques you can find all of them you can find in the commentaries it's not that he made them up but somehow he put them together in a way and he himself was an inspiration where it began a new school that's basically what happened and it usually happens when

35
00:06:55,762 --> 00:07:03,550
there isn't much meditation about, it's sort of faded, and then you get this sort of revival.

36
00:07:04,812 --> 00:07:18,324
And the Mahāsīs probably, he and a man called Ubākin, who began a system also, mainly, we know it mainly through Goenka and his centers in the West.

37
00:07:20,206 --> 00:07:23,069
And these two really did affect the whole Theravādin world.

38
00:07:24,247 --> 00:07:29,935
and with their methodology.

39
00:07:29,995 --> 00:07:42,651
He himself was interesting because he was actually a scholar, a renowned scholar, and this meant that he was the sort of person who was very much up in his head.

40
00:07:42,692 --> 00:07:47,757
So the technique he uses of noting is specifically good.

41
00:07:48,548 --> 00:07:54,797
for those people who are headbound, just to keep the thoughts from not wandering away.

42
00:07:55,838 --> 00:07:58,903
And I've always presumed that's why he developed it.

43
00:07:59,685 --> 00:08:09,139
I've never been able to determine whether that's right or not, but it definitely works in keeping the mind still on the object.

44
00:08:13,625 --> 00:08:18,351
I think the other thing you have to be careful of when you come on a retreat is again this business of gaining something.

45
00:08:21,857 --> 00:08:29,767
If you have in mind a goal then of course all your efforts move towards that goal and in doing so you sort of miss everything.

46
00:08:30,689 --> 00:08:42,044
It's like people who go for walks in the country and their idea is just to get to where they're going and they're like that and they get there but they're sort of missed out on the country.

47
00:08:43,121 --> 00:08:45,946
So be careful that you don't have any goal.

48
00:08:46,025 --> 00:08:55,357
It's best just to be completely open and let the practice itself manifest what it has to offer you.

49
00:08:56,839 --> 00:09:04,428
It's like going to a country, a strange country for the first time, and you've got no particular idea of what it is you want to see.

50
00:09:05,070 --> 00:09:07,493
Well, of course, when you go there, you're very open, you see.

51
00:09:08,130 --> 00:09:09,852
and you tend to see much more.

52
00:09:10,192 --> 00:09:15,960
But if you go there with just the idea of seeing ancient sites or tasting the food and what not, that's all you get.

53
00:09:17,541 --> 00:09:25,330
So have that sort of attitude of just open exploration and then you'll see it offers you quite a lot.

54
00:09:26,892 --> 00:09:34,240
So it offers you an understanding of your physicality, of your body.

55
00:09:34,259 --> 00:09:37,243
It offers you an understanding of your psyche

56
00:09:38,302 --> 00:09:41,365
And by the word psyche, I'm referring to the heart and mind.

57
00:09:42,226 --> 00:09:46,030
We've sort of lost the word which combines those two ever since.

58
00:09:47,673 --> 00:09:50,796
And we can blame Descartes, you know, blame somebody.

59
00:09:50,816 --> 00:09:52,417
Because he split off the mind, didn't he?

60
00:09:52,457 --> 00:09:53,839
And everybody got head bound.

61
00:09:55,441 --> 00:10:03,688
But in the old way of explaining the human being, there was, you know, there was a word which conjoined both the heart and the mind in one.

62
00:10:03,969 --> 00:10:06,572
So we had the word soul, psyche,

63
00:10:08,594 --> 00:10:11,238
And we sort of lost that a bit.

64
00:10:11,859 --> 00:10:19,830
So now we have to keep saying the heart and the mind, or emotions and thoughts, but in a sense they're both one and the same process.

65
00:10:20,630 --> 00:10:22,494
They're just two sides of the same process.

66
00:10:24,956 --> 00:10:33,690
So it's an ability to recognize just how the psyche works, how these two things work, and how we create the world.

67
00:10:37,129 --> 00:10:39,312
And of course there's spiritual insights.

68
00:10:39,933 --> 00:10:52,010
In Buddhism a spiritual insight isn't to do with some sort of transcendental communication with another being or something like that.

69
00:10:52,532 --> 00:11:01,725
A spiritual insight in Buddhist understanding is the final level of consciousness.

70
00:11:03,148 --> 00:11:03,508
That's what it is.

71
00:11:05,210 --> 00:11:17,129
So if you look at the evolution of consciousness, not just in terms of the beings that you see like animals and all that, but just in ourselves, from the point where we are born to where we are now.

72
00:11:18,831 --> 00:11:23,880
We don't think like a newborn baby, I don't think it's possible.

73
00:11:24,942 --> 00:11:25,844
We've all lost that.

74
00:11:26,203 --> 00:11:28,427
We don't think like a three-year-old anymore.

75
00:11:28,447 --> 00:11:30,812
We don't have the magic anymore.

76
00:11:31,635 --> 00:11:35,562
To about the age of seven we live in a world where we believe what we imagine.

77
00:11:37,605 --> 00:11:39,488
That's why Father Christmas can come down the chimney.

78
00:11:39,849 --> 00:11:40,389
No problem.

79
00:11:41,650 --> 00:11:46,038
So all these things manifest a different relationship to the world.

80
00:11:46,798 --> 00:11:53,629
And what we're trying to do is to take that process of consciousness, that process of relationship, to the very end.

81
00:11:54,331 --> 00:11:56,214
And what manifests at the very end?

82
00:11:56,995 --> 00:12:00,360
The very end is in a complete accommodation with the way it is.

83
00:12:01,471 --> 00:12:12,187
There's no struggle, there's no wanting for what other than is given and there's no attempt to destroy or annihilate what we don't want.

84
00:12:14,750 --> 00:12:19,557
So it's a contentment with the way things are, whether they be pleasant or unpleasant.

85
00:12:20,879 --> 00:12:22,942
And that's the state of non-suffering.

86
00:12:23,724 --> 00:12:27,629
It doesn't mean to say you don't have physical pain, it's just natural to the body.

87
00:12:28,927 --> 00:12:37,076
but in terms of the heart-mind, the psyche, it manifests a very different relationship.

88
00:12:37,096 --> 00:12:56,537
And for that to happen there has to be this pulling out, as it were, of its confusion with the body and the psyche, this psycho-physical organism of our intelligence, this intuitive intelligence.

89
00:12:56,855 --> 00:12:59,097
And now all these techniques are to do with that.

90
00:12:59,398 --> 00:13:00,539
That's all.

91
00:13:00,559 --> 00:13:04,245
All these, you know, when I talk about distancing, I mean objectifying.

92
00:13:05,046 --> 00:13:10,592
I mean being able to turn the inside as objective as we now see the outside.

93
00:13:11,214 --> 00:13:13,517
You know, you don't come into this room and say, this is me.

94
00:13:14,759 --> 00:13:15,639
You'd be put away.

95
00:13:16,783 --> 00:13:17,965
Inside, that's all we're doing.

96
00:13:18,004 --> 00:13:28,696
We're turning all this inner furniture, this inner environment, these inner walls that we see, the body and all that, we're turning it very slowly into an objective world.

97
00:13:30,758 --> 00:13:33,640
And in so doing, we're no longer reacting with it.

98
00:13:34,121 --> 00:13:36,163
And that's what produces this inner peace.

99
00:13:37,485 --> 00:13:44,832
Even when you're disturbed, even when you're angry, when you're stressed, you can still find a still small point within that storm, you see.

100
00:13:47,210 --> 00:13:49,913
So that's what these techniques are hoping to do.

101
00:13:50,953 --> 00:13:56,941
And of course, not just here, but to actually take them into daily life.

102
00:13:56,961 --> 00:13:58,802
It's something that is contiguous.

103
00:13:58,822 --> 00:14:02,986
You can't stop spiritual practice like climbing a mountain.

104
00:14:03,047 --> 00:14:06,750
If you stop, you can stop so long and then you get cold and you want to come down at the end of that.

105
00:14:08,113 --> 00:14:08,854
You've got to keep going.

106
00:14:09,153 --> 00:14:11,395
So it's the same with spiritual practice.

107
00:14:15,520 --> 00:14:16,542
Well, you can't stop it.

108
00:14:16,740 --> 00:14:19,183
You've got to keep going once you're in it, you see.

109
00:14:19,203 --> 00:14:28,615
In other words, now that you know, or for some of you beginning to intuit this level of consciousness, you can't go back on it.

110
00:14:28,916 --> 00:14:30,217
It's a piece of knowledge, you know it.

111
00:14:34,383 --> 00:14:43,474
And this awareness that we have, this intuitive awareness that we have, will always be in some way or other wanting to seek its own liberation.

112
00:14:43,594 --> 00:14:44,975
So this is beyond

113
00:14:45,309 --> 00:15:10,001
beyond the idea of some sort of me or mine it's something deep within us which seeks liberation and that's what we really mean by the Buddha so if we just consider some of the techniques now this noting so

114
00:15:10,082 --> 00:15:14,990
The noting is primarily, as far as I'm concerned, is to contain the thinking mind.

115
00:15:15,470 --> 00:15:19,535
But it also has the effect of pointing you to actually look at something.

116
00:15:20,157 --> 00:15:23,081
And the Mahāsī talked about it like throwing a stone at a wall.

117
00:15:23,480 --> 00:15:25,323
So it's like making you.

118
00:15:26,304 --> 00:15:32,614
So as you say, rising, rising, rising, it's like it's pushing your attention to where you want to see.

119
00:15:34,248 --> 00:16:01,167
it's like a push towards it now one of the problems that might come up is that the word seems to get in the way of what you're looking at it seems to be very loud in the mind it seems to in a sense obscure what it is you're looking at now when that happens you see what does that tell us it tells us that our intelligence this satipaññā is locked into the intellect

120
00:16:02,293 --> 00:16:05,740
In other words, it's always seeing things through the intellect.

121
00:16:06,982 --> 00:16:10,448
Now, in our daily life, this is sometimes quite obvious to us.

122
00:16:10,850 --> 00:16:20,967
I mean, even if we take a flower, these, I've forgotten the name of them.

123
00:16:20,988 --> 00:16:21,809
No, no, this one here.

124
00:16:21,870 --> 00:16:24,774
Oh, kids, thank you very much.

125
00:16:25,952 --> 00:16:32,100
You see, when you look at an orchid, if you've seen lots of orchids, you don't really see that orchid.

126
00:16:32,561 --> 00:16:37,407
What you're seeing is fitting into your conception of an orchid, from all the other orchids you've seen.

127
00:16:37,427 --> 00:16:41,611
It sort of flips into a category of orchids.

128
00:16:42,592 --> 00:16:46,677
And we trick ourselves in thinking that we're actually seeing that orchid.

129
00:16:47,535 --> 00:17:03,908
But it's only when you begin to place your eye on it and really see it, really actually see the delicacy of it and the different little bits and pieces that in a sense the word orchid begins to disappear because what you're seeing is something quite unique.

130
00:17:04,765 --> 00:17:07,429
And this is something you can practice while you're here.

131
00:17:07,950 --> 00:17:12,615
The flowers are coming out and you can just place your eye on it.

132
00:17:13,376 --> 00:17:25,815
And you'll see that by just doing that, by saying the word looking rather than naming the flower, you'll see that very slowly you just become quite concentrated upon what the flower is offering you.

133
00:17:27,176 --> 00:17:29,220
The flower doesn't want to be categorized.

134
00:17:31,057 --> 00:17:35,721
And that's clarifying this ability to see things as they really are.

135
00:17:37,303 --> 00:17:40,906
That's one of the pat phrases that you get throughout the scriptures.

136
00:17:40,926 --> 00:17:42,667
To see things as they really are.

137
00:17:42,807 --> 00:17:45,911
To see and understand things as they really are.

138
00:17:46,092 --> 00:17:48,753
Not as I would wish them to be, as I think they are.

139
00:17:49,595 --> 00:17:54,358
And thinking that we know something is one of our big delusions, isn't it?

140
00:17:55,621 --> 00:17:56,922
I think.

141
00:17:57,461 --> 00:18:00,085
Confuse the thought with the actual experience.

142
00:18:00,705 --> 00:18:14,064
So a word actually helps us to just stay there so long as the word is reflecting more the process that we're doing like looking, seeing, touching, feeling.

143
00:18:16,267 --> 00:18:23,936
I don't mean to say that in certain things we can't use a noting word to describe what it is we're experiencing which is pain or something like that.

144
00:18:26,861 --> 00:18:27,961
And

145
00:18:28,599 --> 00:18:38,813
The noting word also just helps us as it were to keep a distance because it's sort of as it were in a sense anyway pushing the object away so that we can actually note it.

146
00:18:40,275 --> 00:18:44,661
It's all part of that process of pushing something away to look at it more clearly.

147
00:18:46,202 --> 00:18:55,755
When we get involved in a pain or an emotion that falling into an identity with it we can't see it because in a sense we're suffering it.

148
00:18:56,308 --> 00:19:24,375
the more concerned with how I feel about it rather than seeing it objectively so when for instance pain comes from the posture of your back or your knee see that's an opportunity to just say pain pain and the more you say it you see the more it pushes away you can see it objectively so the word has it does have an effect on the way that you're looking

149
00:19:25,958 --> 00:19:38,990
And if it does have this effect of being in between you and the word, see, just keep the noting going, but keep putting the attention on the object, and very slowly the word, as it were, disappears.

150
00:19:39,050 --> 00:19:45,817
It begins to move into the background, as it were, and it's like a background note which is pushing you forward.

151
00:19:46,479 --> 00:19:53,586
And this tells a meditator that this intelligence they have is slowly emerging out of its confusion with thought.

152
00:19:54,982 --> 00:19:59,526
So if you find that, just keep gently working at it.

153
00:20:02,375 --> 00:20:08,602
Now the other thing about noting is it has to be deliberate because it's actually an act of noting.

154
00:20:09,542 --> 00:20:16,769
So that's why some of you have already noticed that you can be happily sat here saying rising, falling, your mind's miles away.

155
00:20:17,151 --> 00:20:19,574
When you come back you're still saying rising, falling.

156
00:20:20,575 --> 00:20:27,602
And that tells us how mechanical it can become and how easy it is to create a habit in the body.

157
00:20:28,242 --> 00:20:29,344
Create a habit in the body.

158
00:20:30,032 --> 00:20:37,907
I mean, again, going back to sports and musical instruments, you know, just running up and down the scales of a piano, the fingers just do it.

159
00:20:37,928 --> 00:20:38,970
They don't have to think about it.

160
00:20:40,152 --> 00:20:43,238
Even for us, when we walk across the road, we don't have to think about our legs.

161
00:20:44,299 --> 00:20:45,383
You'd have to think about your legs.

162
00:20:45,462 --> 00:20:46,344
It's terrible, isn't it?

163
00:20:46,785 --> 00:20:49,289
But you just go, and the legs sort of follow you.

164
00:20:50,569 --> 00:21:18,837
moving up and down flapping away underneath you and you don't notice that and if you consider lots of things that you do it's all automated it's all right and thank heavens for it thank heavens for it here however we are trying to be mindful even of the minutest movements because we want to really catch intention and we'll come to that the importance of catching intentions towards the end

165
00:21:20,876 --> 00:21:22,921
So that's the noting business.

166
00:21:24,143 --> 00:21:30,596
And the other thing is of course to keep it going until it becomes quite habitual and it just stays there.

167
00:21:30,635 --> 00:21:36,287
Now one of the reasons it becomes habitual is because every day we're doing the same thing.

168
00:21:37,076 --> 00:21:37,877
It's really boring.

169
00:21:38,598 --> 00:21:42,682
Seven days of doing exactly the same thing.

170
00:21:42,702 --> 00:21:48,509
You walk from here to the dining room, you eat, then you go to your bedroom, you go back, then you come back here.

171
00:21:48,829 --> 00:21:49,871
You're always doing the same thing.

172
00:21:50,372 --> 00:22:04,586
And this makes it very easy to really make very clear to ourselves the process of thought, of intentions, of actions.

173
00:22:05,596 --> 00:22:13,785
When I did this long retreat with my teacher in Burma, all day long I was stuck in a room like this.

174
00:22:14,005 --> 00:22:16,667
We didn't go out because the windows are open, there's no point.

175
00:22:16,688 --> 00:22:19,310
And it's too hot anyway, and the sun.

176
00:22:19,330 --> 00:22:23,115
So all day long I'm in this room, sitting and walking, never going out.

177
00:22:23,135 --> 00:22:26,338
And then there were two times, or three times we went out.

178
00:22:26,859 --> 00:22:29,061
One for breakfast, one for lunch, and one for a drink.

179
00:22:29,682 --> 00:22:33,207
And it was just down the stairs, across the yard, and you sat at a table.

180
00:22:33,929 --> 00:22:36,133
And the breakfast was always the same.

181
00:22:37,736 --> 00:22:39,159
Lunch was slightly different.

182
00:22:39,179 --> 00:22:44,328
And the drink was always the same, this sort of dreadful chemical orange juice.

183
00:22:46,432 --> 00:22:50,300
And then you went back up, up the same stairs, across the same way.

184
00:22:50,482 --> 00:23:00,458
And what that does is, of course, it begins to make it very, very simple to watch the most minutest movement of the body and mind.

185
00:23:01,220 --> 00:23:02,781
Because you're not thinking.

186
00:23:02,942 --> 00:23:04,684
There's no choice left.

187
00:23:04,964 --> 00:23:08,951
You don't say to yourself, now, shall I go down this way or shall I go down that way?

188
00:23:08,991 --> 00:23:09,913
No, you go down this way.

189
00:23:09,932 --> 00:23:11,174
There's only one way to get there.

190
00:23:13,720 --> 00:23:23,314
So by sweeping away any idea of choice and confusing choice with freedom, you're simply doing what you have to do, you see.

191
00:23:23,654 --> 00:23:27,580
And the more you restrict yourself, the less the mind has to think about what you have to do.

192
00:23:27,621 --> 00:23:36,453
And this means that you can really, really settle down to observing the minutiae of how the body and mind work, you see.

193
00:23:37,345 --> 00:23:48,441
Now, the reason for that, of course, is that when you see how it works, and we're specifically interested in how we create suffering for ourselves, then, of course, you see the way out.

194
00:23:50,443 --> 00:23:56,192
Unless we can see how it is that we create problems for ourselves, we're not going to see a solution.

195
00:23:56,753 --> 00:24:01,901
But when you see how we create the problem, then the solution manifests at the same time.

196
00:24:02,082 --> 00:24:03,723
That's all the Buddha did.

197
00:24:03,703 --> 00:24:09,519
Remember, we're following the same path as this ancient personage 2,500 years ago.

198
00:24:09,559 --> 00:24:19,366
I mean, he just sat under a tree and walked about a bit and sat under a tree and walked about a bit and he began to see, you know, where the suffering was arising from.

199
00:24:24,021 --> 00:24:46,214
So that habitual practice and the noting you see, it just allows us to go deeper and deeper into the process of mentation, the process of the body.

200
00:24:48,777 --> 00:24:52,061
I think that's just about covers of noting.

201
00:24:52,362 --> 00:24:56,248
Does anybody else have any questions or something about noting as such?

202
00:24:57,130 --> 00:24:57,911
Have I missed something?

203
00:24:59,773 --> 00:25:02,458
I suppose one thing is not to worry about the word too much.

204
00:25:02,857 --> 00:25:06,683
Sometimes there are many experiences we have for which there just isn't a word.

205
00:25:10,890 --> 00:25:13,173
Just a general word, feeling, thinking, you see.

206
00:25:14,015 --> 00:25:16,759
Always remembering what the word is trying to do.

207
00:25:17,093 --> 00:25:25,803
If we find ourselves getting caught up in, is this the right word or the wrong word, and we're searching for a dictionary, then we've definitely lost the plot.

208
00:25:28,506 --> 00:25:29,106
Can I ask a question?

209
00:25:29,126 --> 00:25:42,020
Is there sort of tension between the benefit of noting in objectifying whatever it is, but at the same time the desire to actually experience it?

210
00:25:46,404 --> 00:25:53,653
but at the same time you're trying to also be fully conscious of the experience.

211
00:25:53,673 --> 00:25:58,557
No, that's a really crucial point to understand.

212
00:25:59,818 --> 00:26:13,272
The word helps us to push away so that we get some objectivity, some sort of witnessing, some sort of ability to be objective with what it is that we are trying to experience.

213
00:26:14,468 --> 00:26:44,424
then as it were once you've got that position of being objective once you've got that position where you know that you're not being caught up in the feeling or the emotion one then as it were goes towards it you see and hopefully through you know during the week sometime hopefully just through that the power of that curiosity and the power of that focus

214
00:26:44,522 --> 00:27:07,569
there's as it were a collapse into the object the word disappears and there's just the pure experience now that's really your true vipassana moment but that you can't make happen this is the point because then at that point the self also disappears it's like when you fall asleep where are you?

215
00:27:07,589 --> 00:27:08,130
where have you gone?

216
00:27:08,750 --> 00:27:09,551
and who wakes up?

217
00:27:11,692 --> 00:27:33,548
so it's like you're moving towards that just by this noting but it's the interest and the curiosity which will draw you towards the object you're trying to understand and feel presumably the moment that you do achieve that kind of being in that experience

218
00:27:35,688 --> 00:27:38,571
The moment you notice that, you've lost it.

219
00:27:38,592 --> 00:27:39,172
Exactly that.

220
00:27:39,913 --> 00:27:40,934
Yes, that's right.

221
00:27:41,075 --> 00:27:47,001
It's one of these paradoxes that you're most happy when you don't know it.

222
00:27:47,583 --> 00:27:49,164
As soon as you know you're happy, you've lost it.

223
00:27:51,327 --> 00:27:52,368
It's like when you watch a film.

224
00:27:52,749 --> 00:27:55,492
You're perfectly happy, completely enthralled by the film.

225
00:27:56,153 --> 00:27:57,796
And then it ends.

226
00:27:57,816 --> 00:27:58,876
That's it, you've lost it.

227
00:28:00,307 --> 00:28:25,826
But our aim is really to become very intimate with the body, heart and mind, and not to be too concerned about that business of losing, you know, becoming, collapsing into that process, because that happens naturally when the conditions are right.

228
00:28:28,050 --> 00:28:51,425
Even at the level of objectivity, you can still, you're still having insights, spiritual insights, because you are observing impermanence, you're observing your reaction to things, you see, and you're also, by creating that distance, recognizing that what you're looking at can't be what's looking, because you're looking at it.

229
00:28:51,540 --> 00:28:56,949
So these themselves are true spiritual insights.

230
00:28:56,969 --> 00:29:02,218
And again, remember, what we mean by spiritual insights is a change in the way we relate to the world.

231
00:29:03,599 --> 00:29:10,471
These are radical ways, radical changes in the way that we see the world.

232
00:29:11,352 --> 00:29:19,084
So if you notice a pattern of thinking, say judging for example, so if you notice that the thoughts that come into your mind

233
00:29:19,537 --> 00:29:26,414
of judgmental of either of yourself or of other people on a repetitive basis on a frequent basis.

234
00:29:26,434 --> 00:29:30,065
You notice a sort of habit of that.

235
00:29:30,085 --> 00:29:35,740
Then what's the process for reflecting on that which doesn't involve

236
00:29:36,259 --> 00:29:39,644
Is there a process for reflecting on it?

237
00:29:39,664 --> 00:29:48,656
Well, if, for instance, something like that is coming up, you know, as a constant judging, judging, you see, the first thing to recognize is that you can't change that.

238
00:29:48,978 --> 00:29:49,699
It's a conditioning.

239
00:29:49,719 --> 00:29:52,502
It has to run its course.

240
00:29:52,522 --> 00:29:56,888
And it'll run its course and empty itself of its energy so long as we don't identify.

241
00:29:58,230 --> 00:30:00,914
And by noting it as judging, you're not identifying.

242
00:30:01,315 --> 00:30:02,537
Otherwise, you'd be judging.

243
00:30:03,242 --> 00:30:05,744
But you can hear these little judgments going on.

244
00:30:06,425 --> 00:30:07,006
I'm no good.

245
00:30:07,846 --> 00:30:08,507
She's no good.

246
00:30:08,708 --> 00:30:09,488
They're no good.

247
00:30:10,929 --> 00:30:11,690
They're better than me.

248
00:30:11,890 --> 00:30:13,030
I'm worse than them.

249
00:30:13,090 --> 00:30:15,633
And you see, you just hear that going on.

250
00:30:16,134 --> 00:30:23,279
But by just observing it and noting it, it no longer has power over you.

251
00:30:23,299 --> 00:30:23,880
That's the point.

252
00:30:27,943 --> 00:30:32,827
But we'll deal with those things more clearly tomorrow when we talk more about the hindrances.

253
00:30:33,060 --> 00:31:01,785
so sitting so remember that your sitting posture is you know the very physical representation of the enlightened mind because there is that alertness in the posture the energy but there's also to be the relaxation and those two are the qualities of your observation a relaxed but alert looking

254
00:31:02,592 --> 00:31:07,462
And of course that's difficult for us because one way we either fall asleep or the other way we get tense, you know.

255
00:31:07,844 --> 00:31:13,478
And it's just being aware of that and just bringing, it's always starting with that calmness, you see.

256
00:31:14,098 --> 00:31:17,386
Starting with the calmness and then raising the curiosity.

257
00:31:18,107 --> 00:31:19,250
That's the way to do it.

258
00:31:20,934 --> 00:31:23,137
And don't struggle with pain.

259
00:31:23,598 --> 00:31:38,278
The tell-tale is, as soon as pain, whether it's physical or emotional, has actually made it difficult to investigate, then that's it, you cut, you go for a walk, you take a break.

260
00:31:39,000 --> 00:31:42,404
There's no point, you see, because this is a process of investigation.

261
00:31:42,444 --> 00:31:44,968
If you can't do it, what's the point of suffering it?

262
00:31:45,741 --> 00:31:47,724
And then, of course, one builds up a resistance.

263
00:31:48,165 --> 00:31:50,469
You can take a bit more pain and all that sort of stuff.

264
00:31:50,489 --> 00:31:53,272
You can hang around with very difficult emotions more.

265
00:31:55,876 --> 00:32:04,650
And I think you have to be slightly careful not to push that because you can frighten yourself.

266
00:32:04,670 --> 00:32:05,592
That's one of the problems.

267
00:32:06,573 --> 00:32:08,516
And just go easy with things.

268
00:32:10,338 --> 00:32:11,901
In the long-term view...

269
00:32:12,234 --> 00:32:39,576
in the Buddha's understanding so long as there's a self there's going to be an existence so we have an eternity of time to sort this one out there's no need to get into a panicky rush about it and even if we are more inclined to believe in one life then the meditation works in that it's at least sorting out this present moment and hopefully we'll make

270
00:32:39,978 --> 00:32:42,482
our future life a bit more easy to live with.

271
00:32:46,771 --> 00:32:49,597
That's the important thing about the sitting posture.

272
00:32:49,958 --> 00:32:56,551
Don't struggle with pain to the point where you can't do the investigation.

273
00:32:58,404 --> 00:33:02,369
Now, the walking, you see, is really important.

274
00:33:02,470 --> 00:33:09,978
People tend not to see its importance, but it's extremely good for developing this calm attentiveness.

275
00:33:10,638 --> 00:33:14,844
It's very calming, and you don't have to go so slow.

276
00:33:15,183 --> 00:33:21,290
When you're going so slow like that, like we do in the evening, that's really also to investigate.

277
00:33:21,507 --> 00:33:49,674
because the feeling of the foot rising is different from the feeling of the foot moving forward is different from the feeling of the foot falling and it's different from the feeling of the foot pressing and it's these discriminations that are making that are sort of tuning this intelligence making it more sharp to see things that previously would have just seen as just one feeling the foot moving through the air

278
00:33:50,920 --> 00:33:57,003
But you can also use walking gently up and down just to develop this calm abiding.

279
00:33:58,611 --> 00:34:00,458
So it's a very powerful exercise.

280
00:34:01,518 --> 00:34:04,181
So don't, you know, try and do as much of it as you can.

281
00:34:04,280 --> 00:34:21,679
I know there's a tendency to rush off for a cup of tea, but, and there's nothing wrong with having a cup of tea, you understand, but often it sort of lengthens out to 40 minutes, and then you do a 10-minute walk and come back and sit.

282
00:34:22,081 --> 00:34:29,449
But it's much better if you do want to have a beverage and make it short and sweet, and really just keep walking up and down, yeah?

283
00:34:37,630 --> 00:34:43,168
Going slow, so that's his other big technique, the Mahāzī's technique.

284
00:34:47,400 --> 00:34:53,211
Really try to, you know, if you find yourself rushing anywhere, just stop.

285
00:34:53,813 --> 00:34:55,916
Just stop in your tracks.

286
00:34:55,936 --> 00:34:56,177
See?

287
00:34:56,998 --> 00:34:58,681
And just let the energy fall away.

288
00:34:59,344 --> 00:35:00,465
And then just take your time.

289
00:35:01,306 --> 00:35:06,076
I don't think you ought to be going faster than left, right, left, right.

290
00:35:06,396 --> 00:35:07,038
That's about it.

291
00:35:07,418 --> 00:35:09,121
If you're going faster than that, you're rushing.

292
00:35:11,347 --> 00:35:35,835
and try to find little things during the day when you can really take your time now this door for instance you see you can actually open and close it completely silently you don't have to bang it to or push it and you can you can make the opening of that door a specific exercise I always know where people are by how they go out through that door

293
00:35:37,552 --> 00:35:39,655
Pushing the door open to your bedroom, you see.

294
00:35:39,795 --> 00:35:44,541
Just do it very slowly and just sort of communicate with the spring, you know.

295
00:35:46,465 --> 00:35:48,648
Certain things you can't go so slow.

296
00:35:48,668 --> 00:35:50,170
You can't brush your teeth at that speed.

297
00:35:50,190 --> 00:35:50,891
You'd never finish.

298
00:35:52,873 --> 00:35:57,139
But there are many things that you can do where you're not actually holding anybody up.

299
00:35:57,179 --> 00:36:00,342
That's the other thing about the bathroom.

300
00:36:00,362 --> 00:36:01,545
There may be people waiting.

301
00:36:02,065 --> 00:36:05,670
But there are many things that you can do which you can go really slowly at.

302
00:36:06,628 --> 00:36:08,052
And just observe it.

303
00:36:08,072 --> 00:36:10,115
And the main place, of course, is when you're eating.

304
00:36:13,543 --> 00:36:18,612
If you finish before me, you're definitely going too fast.

305
00:36:18,632 --> 00:36:22,981
Because I'm eating at what I would consider to be an ordinary pace.

306
00:36:23,503 --> 00:36:24,385
An ordinary pace.

307
00:36:29,275 --> 00:36:31,639
And of course, the more you go slow, the more you see.

308
00:36:31,659 --> 00:36:44,719
I mean, we've all seen these films on TV of nature, you know, like a butterfly or these hummingbirds, how their wings flap and you can actually see it.

309
00:36:45,762 --> 00:36:48,085
And it's just slowing the film down frame by frame.

310
00:36:48,666 --> 00:36:49,608
So that's all we're doing.

311
00:36:49,648 --> 00:36:52,632
The slower you go, the more you'll actually see.

312
00:36:53,034 --> 00:36:54,135
You'll see the connection.

313
00:36:54,836 --> 00:36:57,679
So we chant this dependent origination in the morning.

314
00:36:58,278 --> 00:37:14,012
So the Buddha there, I mean I'll go into it more deeply towards the end of the week, but the Buddha there is showing us that although we experience life as one continuous thought process, thought emotional process, actually there's myriads of little processes going on.

315
00:37:14,672 --> 00:37:19,257
And what we're catching are sort of end products.

316
00:37:19,277 --> 00:37:22,619
And these processes are going on continuously throughout the day.

317
00:37:23,797 --> 00:37:38,574
Even, as you know, even to see something, there has to be a process whereby, you know, what hits the retina has to be sensed in the mind, it has to be categorized, it has to be put into some sort of picture.

318
00:37:38,835 --> 00:37:41,639
And what we see is the final product, the picture.

319
00:37:42,739 --> 00:37:43,820
Same with hearing.

320
00:37:43,840 --> 00:37:48,827
There's a whole process going on from the point where all there is is pressure on the eardrum.

321
00:37:49,481 --> 00:37:58,179
By the time we get to alarm bell or bell to sit, that's gone through a whole load of mental processes to get there.

322
00:37:58,199 --> 00:38:01,166
But what we're always aware of is the end product.

323
00:38:04,432 --> 00:38:09,903
And what we're also specifically interested in is not just the way that...

324
00:38:10,036 --> 00:38:32,009
we produce a certain concreteness about our existence, a certain substantiality, whereas in fact it's all these myriad processes going on, is to see it as something transient, but also we're interested in this relationship we have, wanting, not wanting, wanting, not wanting, wanting, not wanting.

325
00:38:32,108 --> 00:38:38,338
And that's another level of this mental process, which for the most part we're not really aware of,

326
00:38:39,061 --> 00:38:46,690
You know, just watching people around supermarkets, they don't distinguish the product that they're looking at and the wanting of it.

327
00:38:47,590 --> 00:38:48,711
It's already my product.

328
00:38:49,213 --> 00:38:51,215
As soon as they see it, it's my product.

329
00:38:51,235 --> 00:38:52,135
They've already bought it.

330
00:38:55,820 --> 00:39:04,650
And that for us is very important, to see the distinction between liking something, disliking something, and wanting and not wanting.

331
00:39:04,990 --> 00:39:06,072
Pleasant, unpleasant.

332
00:39:06,313 --> 00:39:07,414
Wanting, not wanting.

333
00:39:08,507 --> 00:39:15,295
And that will become more and more obvious to us the more we slow that process down.

334
00:39:16,918 --> 00:39:22,144
So make an effort over the next few days to just take your time, basically.

335
00:39:22,784 --> 00:39:23,365
Take your time.

336
00:39:26,289 --> 00:39:30,735
So finally there's this intention.

337
00:39:32,909 --> 00:40:01,835
intention in now first of all what we mean by an intention here is a desire right it's not been empowered so it's a desire which is arising is a very important moment in Buddhist psychology because as a desire it's not having a conditioning effect it's not an action it just lies as a potential in the mind

338
00:40:03,081 --> 00:40:16,217
But if we act on it, or as they put it in these awful committee speak, if you action it, then it immediately becomes an act.

339
00:40:16,878 --> 00:40:20,842
And once that happens, it will have a conditioning effect within us.

340
00:40:20,862 --> 00:40:22,804
And of course, it will produce something.

341
00:40:23,465 --> 00:40:26,228
If it's wholesome, it will produce something wholesome within us.

342
00:40:26,889 --> 00:40:31,215
If it's unskillful, it will produce something unwholesome.

343
00:40:33,793 --> 00:40:41,041
So that's why the accent is always on when you're sitting and you hear the bell go or you've done the reflections and it's time to go up.

344
00:40:41,681 --> 00:40:42,882
Intending to rise.

345
00:40:45,184 --> 00:40:47,226
So now you're empowered, you see.

346
00:40:48,027 --> 00:40:49,548
You're not acting like an automaton.

347
00:40:49,588 --> 00:40:51,490
You're watching the intention arise.

348
00:40:51,731 --> 00:40:52,891
Intending to rise.

349
00:40:54,273 --> 00:40:57,775
Now that's the moment you can reflect and say, is this a good thing to do or a bad thing?

350
00:40:58,797 --> 00:41:00,079
Is it skillful or unskillful?

351
00:41:00,099 --> 00:41:01,539
Virtuous or unvirtuous?

352
00:41:02,735 --> 00:41:05,597
That's the only moment you've got in terms of choice.

353
00:41:05,978 --> 00:41:07,460
Once you rise, you've lost it.

354
00:41:08,041 --> 00:41:10,342
You've already created an act.

355
00:41:11,003 --> 00:41:15,108
That's why in the standing meditation, you can stand there and say, intending to walk.

356
00:41:15,208 --> 00:41:16,510
Nothing happens.

357
00:41:16,530 --> 00:41:19,172
You can stand there all day, intending to walk.

358
00:41:20,974 --> 00:41:24,139
Now these intentions, remember, they're not huge, strong desires.

359
00:41:24,159 --> 00:41:25,780
We're not talking about cravings.

360
00:41:26,340 --> 00:41:30,505
We're just talking about a simple intention, a wanting to walk.

361
00:41:30,525 --> 00:41:32,487
And you can stay there with intending, nothing happens.

362
00:41:33,733 --> 00:41:37,380
and then suddenly there's a decision and your foot moves.

363
00:41:38,340 --> 00:41:39,963
So this is a magical moment isn't it?

364
00:41:40,644 --> 00:41:43,650
How does something move out of potential into an actual?

365
00:41:46,293 --> 00:41:54,206
Now that moment of actuality the Buddha actually calls will and at that point there's an act is created

366
00:41:54,389 --> 00:41:56,873
And then you can't stop its problem.

367
00:41:57,355 --> 00:41:59,179
It's already gone into the system.

368
00:41:59,681 --> 00:42:03,769
And if it's something out there, it's gone into the world, and you'll get your response.

369
00:42:06,135 --> 00:42:10,844
And again, we'll talk about karma in that larger sense towards the end of the week.

370
00:42:13,458 --> 00:42:34,989
So that's why when we're eating, you see, rather than get caught up in this natural appetite that we have, just get lost in it, turn it into a greedy thing, just by noting the intention, what desiring to eat, you see, having made a previous intention that you're only eating to nourish the body, and you're reaffirming that intention every time you eat.

371
00:42:35,650 --> 00:42:37,271
So these are conditioning acts.

372
00:42:37,807 --> 00:42:45,704
And the more we condition ourselves to eat to nourish the body, the less we're going to find ourselves with some eating problems.

373
00:42:47,867 --> 00:42:51,315
And that's of course one way to come out of an eating problem if we find we have one.

374
00:42:52,217 --> 00:42:59,731
It's just not reinforcing the intention to eat for comfort's sake or for happiness.

375
00:43:00,775 --> 00:43:27,103
And so intention is a really important thing to note, and if you can at least begin by noting main intentions, which is the intention to rise, the intention to walk somewhere, the intention to start your sitting, the intention to eat, if you can start by noting those, they create a natural break, you see, you're actually stopping for a moment, they're a natural stopping.

376
00:43:27,083 --> 00:43:31,088
And in that moment there's this ability to reflect.

377
00:43:31,108 --> 00:43:39,478
And what this is showing us is that, you know, if we were to take this full time, then we'd become in charge of our lives.

378
00:43:40,940 --> 00:43:52,934
Begin to be in charge of it rather than, you know, behaving by old conditionings or coming under other people's influence.

379
00:43:52,954 --> 00:43:53,074
Right?

380
00:43:55,449 --> 00:43:59,856
we gain our, you might say, autonomy.

381
00:44:02,099 --> 00:44:09,688
So you'll be hearing me constantly encouraging you to note your intention.

382
00:44:09,708 --> 00:44:24,528
There's a little passage in the Visuddhimagga which is a sort of a later commentarial work in which a teacher is teaching his students and at one point he raises his hand and he stops, stops talking

383
00:44:24,695 --> 00:44:27,657
And then he just puts his hand very gently back there, you see.

384
00:44:27,677 --> 00:44:28,918
And his students say, what happened there?

385
00:44:30,641 --> 00:44:32,902
He said, I didn't note the intention.

386
00:44:34,603 --> 00:44:38,208
It was just an old automatic thing that he did.

387
00:44:39,648 --> 00:44:51,039
But if you're quite wide awake, you see, if you're really awake, you'll see it come across the mind, move your hand, intention to move your hand, intention to scratch.

388
00:44:51,914 --> 00:44:54,858
So that's the same with when you get an itch, you see.

389
00:44:55,358 --> 00:44:59,063
So you note your intention.

390
00:44:59,083 --> 00:45:01,827
You try and handle the itch as much as you can, right?

391
00:45:01,847 --> 00:45:04,530
And you see this enormous desire to scratch.

392
00:45:06,112 --> 00:45:17,989
And when you can't take it anymore, say, intending to scratch, and then just watch how the mind reacts to it, how it becomes relieved of its tension once you've given yourself a good scratch.

393
00:45:20,467 --> 00:45:28,217
So, these are your basic components of your practice.

394
00:45:28,237 --> 00:45:41,054
This continuous noting as best as you can, going slow and slower, and trying to choose certain actions during the day where you really do things very slowly, so that you've got a standard.

395
00:45:41,594 --> 00:45:43,336
That's why we walk together in the evening.

396
00:45:44,097 --> 00:45:49,005
There I hope to create a sort of standard for you of going slow.

397
00:45:49,693 --> 00:45:55,342
and then try and do that as much as you can during the day and noting intentions.

398
00:46:02,773 --> 00:46:18,114
Just as when you're intending to eat there's a sort of back story about the intention which is your bigger intention is to only eat for healthy purposes then I suppose for many other intentions

399
00:46:18,719 --> 00:46:47,054
in order to decide rather than simply noting that you're intending to do it and then doing it if there's a possibility of saying I'm not going to do it you need a kind of back story of intention about what's the bigger intention behind the intention it helps it helps to have a sort of large intention so the intention here behind this whole retreat is to develop moment to moment mindfulness that's the purpose of all these techniques

400
00:46:48,739 --> 00:46:57,327
to actually be completely awake to the presenting moment.

401
00:46:57,347 --> 00:47:03,554
And of course our nature is not to stay there.

402
00:47:03,755 --> 00:47:06,737
We like to live in the future or live in the past.

403
00:47:08,039 --> 00:47:11,561
We don't like to be completely in the present moment unless it's really happy.

404
00:47:14,684 --> 00:47:18,409
Unless we're really, really enjoying it.

405
00:47:23,992 --> 00:47:24,472
Is that it?

406
00:47:24,492 --> 00:47:26,253
Any other questions?

407
00:47:26,293 --> 00:47:41,188
We'll meet of course tomorrow in case something comes up.

408
00:47:41,208 --> 00:47:44,652
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

409
00:47:44,672 --> 00:47:49,898
May you be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

410
00:47:53,168 --> 00:47:56,692
Now your response is sadhu, sadhu.

411
00:47:58,574 --> 00:47:59,594
Which means well done, you see.

412
00:48:00,536 --> 00:48:03,277
Now you can imagine how I feel if I don't get sadhu, sadhu.

413
00:48:05,420 --> 00:48:08,483
It's desperate, isn't it?

414
00:48:08,503 --> 00:48:08,784
Very good.

415
00:48:08,864 --> 00:48:15,050
So we have some walking and then at quarter past come in again and I'll come in to do the walking meditation with you.

416
00:48:15,731 --> 00:48:19,614
And we'll sit the last period together and finish with me.

